			<div class="col-sm-8">
				<h3>Dr. Thomas Volk</h3>

				<p>In addition to sharing his pictures, Tom played a vital role in the early development of this web site.
					For this, I am very thankful. </p>

				<p>I applied for a sabbatical leave for the fall of 2003 after serving as department chair during the previous five years.
					My goal for the leave was to pursue scholarship activities in mycology. From talks I heard Tom give over the years,
					I appreciated, as a fellow teacher, his interest and passion for mycological education.
					Tom didn't know me very well but took a step of faith and agreed to collaborate with me.
					He provided encouragement and ideas to consider during the decision making process leading to
					the concept for this web site. His endorsement, as an external collaborator, was important in
					the approval process for my sabbatical. In the fall of 2003, as part of the sabbatical,
					I traveled to La Crosse, WI, and studied with Tom for a week. I sat in on one of his classes,
					went on several forays, met his graduate students, met some of his University colleagues,
					went on a mycology lab field trip, enjoyed the use of his lab, helped him dry apples,
					saw some great sights around La Crosse, and soaked up as much mycology as I could.
					Tom even planted a rhododendron at his home in my honor. Many thanks, Tom,
					for your hospitality and infectious love of fungi.
				</p>

			</div>

